19 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
20 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
21 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
22 The Legislature finds that Oklahoma's groundwater resources face
23 critical threats from depletion and contamination due to unqualified
24 workers and improper water access practices. There is a nationwide
Req. No. 12373 Page 1

1 geos cience workforce shortage projected by the United States
2 Department of Labor to peak at 130,000 workers by 2029, leaving
3 Oklahoma's groundwater industry struggling to fill positions with
4 adequately trained professionals. The growing reliance on untrained
5 workers in the groundwater industry jeopardizes the safety of homes,
6 businesses, and communities and accelerates the degradation of these
7 essential water resources. Immediate action is needed to protect
8 these vital water resources and to equip the groundwater workforce
9 with the skills necessary to ensure sustainable water management
10 practices.
11 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
12 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1020.16a of Title 82, unless
13 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
14 A. There is hereby created the Oklahoma Water Resources Board
15 Well Driller and Pump Installer Program. The Program shall be
16 administered by the Board and shall have the following duties:
17 1. License well drilling and pump installation professionals to
18 ensure the integrity of well construction, and that those
19 professionals are meeting construction standards to prevent
20 pollution of groundwater in Oklahoma;
21 2. Develop comprehensive standards and rules in cooperation
22 with the Well Driller and Pump Installer Advisory Council, the
23 Oklahoma Ground Water Association, and public stakeholders;
24
Req. No. 12373 Page 2

1 3. Provide for training and outreach for licensed well drillers
2 and pump installers;
3 4. Provide technical assistance to the public regarding
4 groundwater and well construction; and
5 5. Focus on funding and supporting the development and
6 expansion of a groundwater professional training program at an
7 accredited Tier 1 research institution of higher education in
8 Oklahoma.
9 B. The groundwater professional training program shall:
10 1. Support and expand an existing groundwater professional
11 training program established by the National Ground Water
12 Association;
13 2. Provide specialized education and skills-based micro-
14 credentials for both current and future groundwater professionals,
15 including water well drillers, pump installers, plumbers, and heavy
16 equipment operators; and
17 3. Partner with state and national industry leaders to ensure
18 workforce training is conducted using cutting-edge, industry-
19 approved methods.
20 C. The Board shall:
21 1. Identify and establish a formal partnership with a
22 qualifying institution of higher education in Oklahoma;
23
